WEBVTT

00:00:00.320 --> 00:00:04.620
Good morning, everyone. And switching over to another rare disease, Waldenstrom. So just

00:00:04.620 --> 00:00:08.600
be talking about the novel approaches for Waldenstrom that are happening right in front

00:00:08.600 --> 00:00:14.160
of our eyes right now. Here are my disclosures. And just the outline of my talk is going to

00:00:14.160 --> 00:00:17.460
cover the current treatment landscape for Waldenstrom. We'll look at some of the emerging

00:00:17.460 --> 00:00:22.900
therapeutic options and then also igniting a conversation around anti-BCMA therapies

00:00:22.900 --> 00:00:29.400
in Waldenstrom. So as we all know, Waldenstrom has shared similarities on a genomic level

00:00:29.400 --> 00:00:35.580
with other indolent B-cell lymphomas as well as multiple myeloma. So all the therapies

00:00:35.580 --> 00:00:39.580
that have been studied in Waldenstrom are either lymphoma therapies or multiple myeloma

00:00:39.580 --> 00:00:44.100
therapies. And these are some of the trials that have looked at treatment in the upfront

00:00:44.100 --> 00:00:51.000
setting of Waldenstrom. And as Dr. Sharosek in a couple of days showed us in her slides

00:00:51.000 --> 00:00:55.660
that when it comes to treating Waldenstrom in the upfront setting, we either use BT

00:00:55.660 --> 00:00:59.100
inhibitors or chemoimmunotherapy. Those are the mainstay of our treatment.

00:00:59.400 --> 00:01:04.740
But there are many other options available as well. When we look at some of the options that

00:01:04.740 --> 00:01:09.780
have been studied in the relapsed refractory setting for Waldenstrom, venetoclax was like,

00:01:09.780 --> 00:01:13.740
you know, one of the therapies that have been looked into. So we know that BCL2 is overexpressed

00:01:13.740 --> 00:01:18.540
in Waldenstrom cells as well. So there was a phase two trial out of Dana-Farber that enrolled 30

00:01:18.540 --> 00:01:24.000
patients who got venetoclax. And it worked for majority of the patients, like about 80% of the

00:01:24.000 --> 00:01:29.340
patients had a major response. And these response were long lasting. The median PFS on this trial was

00:01:29.340 --> 00:01:35.280
two and a half years. Then also at the same time, we had data on pertobrutinib, which is a non-covalent

00:01:35.280 --> 00:01:42.120
PTK inhibitor. And the advantage of pertobrutinib is that it works even after patients have like,

00:01:42.120 --> 00:01:47.820
you know, progressed on xanabrutinib or ibrutinib. So the Bruin trial enrolled around 78 patients

00:01:47.820 --> 00:01:52.140
who had Waldenstrom. And again, we saw something similar to what we saw with venetoclax that

00:01:52.140 --> 00:01:56.220
majority of these patients responded to pertobrutinib. And like, you know,

00:01:56.220 --> 00:01:59.280
the one thing also unique here is that the toxicities were quite

00:01:59.280 --> 00:02:04.440
low compared to what we see with the other BTK inhibitors. And then like, you know, a few years

00:02:04.440 --> 00:02:10.320
ago at ASH, we had heard about like CAR-T cell therapy in Waldenstrom. So there was a CD20 CAR-T

00:02:10.320 --> 00:02:16.020
candidate from Mustang Bio that like, you know, showed that CAR-T was given to these six patients

00:02:16.020 --> 00:02:20.940
and three out of those six patients had deep responses. And there was a trial that was going

00:02:20.940 --> 00:02:25.080
to happen and enroll more Waldenstrom patients, but it looks like it's been terminated since.

00:02:25.860 --> 00:02:29.220
Then other therapies that hold a lot of promise in

00:02:29.220 --> 00:02:33.900
Waldenstrom are the BTK degraders. So they work differently than BTK inhibitors. And I think we

00:02:33.900 --> 00:02:39.180
have heard a lot about BTK degraders in the last few days, including the pipeline review from B1,

00:02:39.180 --> 00:02:47.280
but just to like quickly recap that BTK degraders are where the BTK is ubiquitinated and destroyed.

00:02:47.280 --> 00:02:54.060
So it's not constitutionally active. So we have two different BTK degrader

00:02:54.060 --> 00:02:59.160
candidates that actually have trials going on in Waldenstrom. One is from B1 and the other one is

00:02:59.160 --> 00:03:03.300
from Neurics Pharmaceuticals. And both of these trials have enrolled a small number of patients

00:03:03.300 --> 00:03:08.820
and show that almost everybody's responding when BTK degraders are being used after like,

00:03:08.820 --> 00:03:11.940
you know, that refractoriness or resistance to BTK inhibitors.

00:03:11.940 --> 00:03:18.120
And then like, you know, talking a little bit now about BCMA in Waldenstrom. So in the last

00:03:18.120 --> 00:03:23.820
few years, we have had a few studies that have showed that BCMA expression is also seen in plasma

00:03:23.820 --> 00:03:29.100
cells and these mature B cells present in lymphoplasma-cytic lymphomas. And, you know,

00:03:29.100 --> 00:03:33.720
there are also studies that have looked at serum BCMA levels that in Waldenstrom patients,

00:03:33.720 --> 00:03:40.200
serum BCMA levels are usually three to four times the BCMA level seen in normal healthy controls.

00:03:40.200 --> 00:03:46.080
So I think that also opens up another avenue for treatment in Waldenstrom that some of these BCMA

00:03:46.080 --> 00:03:50.460
therapies, just like how some of the other myeloma therapies like Vulcade have worked

00:03:50.460 --> 00:03:53.820
in Waldenstrom, maybe there is a role for anti-BCMA therapies here as well.

00:03:53.820 --> 00:03:59.040
And I think the next slide is what I'm going to show one of our own experiences of a patient who

00:03:59.040 --> 00:04:06.060
had MYD88 wild-type Waldenstrom and essentially like, you know, started treatment just like how

00:04:06.060 --> 00:04:11.460
our other patients do with a BTK inhibitor and had hyperviscosity at the time of the diagnosis,

00:04:11.460 --> 00:04:16.860
required plasma exchange, got Xanabrutinib, did not respond, then got chemotherapy and through

00:04:16.860 --> 00:04:21.900
this time continued to need plasma exchange from time to time. And then basically went through each

00:04:21.900 --> 00:04:28.980
and every therapy that was available, including Pyrotabrutinib, Venetoclax, some Vulcade-based regimen, and

00:04:28.980 --> 00:04:34.440
including Daratumumab, but like, you know, none of these treatments brought on any durable responses.

00:04:34.440 --> 00:04:38.820
And then ultimately, like, you know, the thought came of what, like using one of the bispecific

00:04:38.820 --> 00:04:44.520
antibodies out there. And because we are a myeloma doctor, we decided, like, let's use one of the

00:04:44.520 --> 00:04:49.560
myeloma bispecifics here. And this patient got Elranatumab, and this was like in August, 2024.

00:04:49.560 --> 00:04:54.540
So it's been a year and a half since. The IgM levels were close to 4,000, and they dropped

00:04:54.540 --> 00:04:58.740
down to less than 20 within a few months of starting Elra. And this patient's maintained that

00:04:58.740 --> 00:05:04.380
response ever since. And like, you know, just the past week, I had a patient with IgM amyloid doses,

00:05:04.380 --> 00:05:12.120
where we had initially tried Daracybordy followed by Bendamustin rituximab without a response that

00:05:12.120 --> 00:05:17.520
we would like to achieve in an amyloid patient. And when I gave that patient teclistamab, like,

00:05:17.520 --> 00:05:22.560
their light chains have, like, dropped from 300 down to 40 just during the ramp up itself of

00:05:22.560 --> 00:05:27.120
teclistamab. So I think, like, some of these examples are going to continue to come out in

00:05:27.120 --> 00:05:31.920
the near future. And they're going to show that, yeah, these BCMA therapies could also have a big

00:05:31.920 --> 00:05:37.320
role in treating Waldenstrom. And I think the game is on in terms of what is the right bispecific

00:05:37.320 --> 00:05:42.480
therapy for Waldenstrom, whether those are BCMA therapies or anti-CD20 bispecific therapies.

00:05:42.480 --> 00:05:48.120
And just to, like, you know, like, conclude my presentation with a few questions that I

00:05:48.120 --> 00:05:52.320
always have in my mind and things that we can improve upon in Waldenstrom. Most of our patients

00:05:52.320 --> 00:05:58.380
do very well. But that means that these patients are indefinitely on a BTK inhibitor. And we know

00:05:58.380 --> 00:06:04.260
that these BTK inhibitor therapy toxicities could be cumulative. About 30% of the patients will stop

00:06:04.260 --> 00:06:09.540
BTK inhibitor because of intolerance. And even, like, you know, side effects like atrial fibrillation,

00:06:09.540 --> 00:06:15.420
these are cumulative risks that will continue to build upon or happen even after many years of

00:06:15.420 --> 00:06:21.840
therapy. And then also we know that some of these patients who are MYD88 wild type or TP53 mutated,

00:06:22.080 --> 00:06:26.340
which is usually the bianelic deletions, like, those are patients who don't respond very long

00:06:26.340 --> 00:06:30.660
with BTK inhibitor. And at the same time, like, you know, other things that we think about is,

00:06:30.660 --> 00:06:35.640
like, when patients do relapse or progress, like, we do have trials, but we really don't have any,

00:06:35.640 --> 00:06:40.560
like, you know, phase three trials in the space, unless you consider the INOVAID-WM trial, which

00:06:40.560 --> 00:06:45.540
looked at ibrutinib to be a phase three trial in the relapse refractory setting. And then I think

00:06:45.540 --> 00:06:50.460
the concept of MRD, which is well established in many other hematologic diseases, is still relatively

00:06:50.460 --> 00:06:55.620
new one, because most of our patients don't get into that deep response. But with some of these

00:06:55.620 --> 00:07:00.660
newer therapies coming out here, I think this is going to be, again, a topic of, like, you know,

00:07:00.660 --> 00:07:05.940
like, hot conversation around whether our patients could be MRD negative and could they be, like,

00:07:05.940 --> 00:07:10.740
you know, could they just receive a definite duration of treatment, achieve MRD negativity,

00:07:10.740 --> 00:07:14.640
and continue to have a long, durable response. And just to, like, you know,

00:07:14.640 --> 00:07:20.220
like, mention here also that this is a very exciting time in Waldenstrom, because all the

00:07:20.220 --> 00:07:24.960
newest advances in the lymphoma world and myeloma world are actually coming into clinical trials in

00:07:24.960 --> 00:07:29.280
Waldenstrom. And this is a table that covers most of the Waldenstrom trials that are going

00:07:29.280 --> 00:07:33.720
on right now, including a trial with mozonertizumab and pertobrutinib that's

00:07:33.720 --> 00:07:37.140
actually opening at our site in the next few months. Thank you for listening.
